SELECT 'Write a debounce function from scratch in JavaScript.', 'coding', '{"modelA":{"text":"function debounce(fn, delay) {\n  let timer;\n  return function (...args) {\n    clearTimeout(timer);\n    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);\n  };\n}\n\nconst handleSearch = debounce((query) => {\n  console.log(''Searching for:'', query);\n}, 300);\n\ndebounce wraps a function so it only fires after the specified delay since the last call. Each new call resets the timer, so rapid-fire invocations only trigger the function once the user pauses.","model_id":"anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-5"},"modelB":{"text":"function debounce(func, wait) {\n  let timeout;\n  return function executedFunction(...args) {\n    const later = () => { clearTimeout(timeout); func(...args); };\n    clearTimeout(timeout);\n    timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);\n  };\n}\n\nHow it works:\n1. Returns a wrapper that clears any pending timer on every call\n2. Sets a new timer for wait milliseconds\n3. Only when the timer completes does it invoke the original function\n\nExample:\nconst debouncedSearch = debounce(searchAPI, 500);\ninput.addEventListener(''input'', (e) => debouncedSearch(e.target.value));","model_id":"openai/gpt-4o"},"modelC":{"text":"function debounce(func, delay) {\n  let timeoutId;\n  return function(...args) {\n    if (timeoutId) clearTimeout(timeoutId);\n    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);\n  };\n}\n\nUsage:\nconst debouncedResize = debounce(() => console.log(''resized!''), 250);\nwindow.addEventListener(''resize'', debouncedResize);\n\nThe key insight is that timeoutId lives in the closure — each call cancels the previous timer and starts fresh.","model_id":"google/gemini-pro-1.5"},"modelD":{"text":"Here''s a clean debounce implementation:\n\nfunction debounce(fn, ms) {\n  let id;\n  return (...args) => {\n    clearTimeout(id);\n    id = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), ms);\n  };\n}\n\nThat''s it. clearTimeout on a null/undefined timer is a no-op, so the check is unnecessary. Arrow function inherits outer this — if you need dynamic this binding, swap the inner arrow for a regular function and use fn.apply(this, args). Typical usage: debounce(saveForm, 400).","model_id":"x-ai/grok-2-1212"},"modelE":{"text":"A debounce function limits how often a function runs by delaying its execution until a pause in calls occurs.\n\nfunction debounce(callback, delay = 300) {\n  let timer = null;\n\n  return function (...args) {\n    clearTimeout(timer);\n    timer = setTimeout(() => {\n      callback.apply(this, args);\n      timer = null;\n    }, delay);\n  };\n}\n\nThe timer = null after execution is a minor improvement — it allows garbage collection of the timeout reference. Common use cases include search inputs, window resize handlers, and form auto-save. Most production codebases use lodash.debounce, but understanding the implementation matters for interviews and edge cases.","model_id":"perplexity/llama-3.1-sonar-large-128k-online"}}'::jsonb, true, '2026-06-11'
