SELECT 'How should I ask for a raise when I know I''m underpaid by 20%?', 'career', '{"modelA":{"text":"Start by building your case before the conversation. Document your contributions — specific projects, metrics, and outcomes that show your value. Research market rates using Glassdoor, Levels.fyi, or LinkedIn Salary to back up the 20% gap with data, not just a feeling.\n\nWhen you schedule the meeting, frame it as a career conversation, not a complaint. Open with your accomplishments, then present the market data. Name the number you want — vague requests get vague answers.\n\nBe ready for pushback. If budget is the excuse, ask about a timeline: \"If not now, what would need to happen for a review in 90 days?\" Get any commitments in writing. If they won''t move at all, you have useful information about whether to stay.","model_id":"anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-5"},"modelB":{"text":"Here''s a strategic approach:\n\n1. Do your homework first\nGather salary data from Glassdoor, LinkedIn Salary, and Levels.fyi. Document your specific achievements and quantify them.\n\n2. Request a dedicated meeting\nDon''t bring it up casually. Ask for time specifically to discuss your compensation.\n\n3. Lead with value, follow with market data\n\"Over the past year, I''ve [accomplishments]. Based on current market rates, I believe there''s a meaningful gap in my compensation.\"\n\n4. State a specific number — vague requests get vague answers.\n\n5. Prepare for objections\n\"Budget is tight\" → Ask about a concrete timeline.\nIf they can''t close the gap, that''s valuable information about whether to stay.","model_id":"openai/gpt-4o"},"modelC":{"text":"Asking for a raise when you''re underpaid requires preparation and confidence.\n\nPrepare your case:\n- Gather market data showing the 20% gap (Glassdoor, LinkedIn Salary, industry reports)\n- List your key accomplishments with measurable impact\n- Time it well — after a recent win or during review cycles\n\nThe conversation:\nSchedule a formal meeting. Open by expressing commitment to the role, then: \"I''ve researched market rates and there''s a significant gap. I''d like to discuss bringing my salary to [specific number].\"\n\nIf they say no, ask what needs to change and request a concrete timeline in writing.","model_id":"google/gemini-pro-1.5"},"modelD":{"text":"20% underpaid is significant. Here''s the direct approach:\n\nPrepare three things: (1) your market rate evidence — Levels.fyi, Glassdoor, a competing offer if you have one, (2) a specific number, not a range, and (3) your actual contributions in concrete terms.\n\nThen say this: \"I''ve done some market research and I''m seeing my role typically pays around $X. I''d like to get to $Y. Can we make that happen?\"\n\nIf they say budget is tight, ask for a timeline and get it in writing. If they can''t commit to anything within six months, start interviewing. A competing offer is the most powerful lever you have — and sometimes the only one that works.","model_id":"x-ai/grok-2-1212"},"modelE":{"text":"Research consistently shows that employees who negotiate salaries earn significantly more over their careers. For a 20% gap, here''s what works:\n\nBefore the meeting:\n- Build your market data case using Levels.fyi, LinkedIn Salary Insights, Glassdoor, and industry-specific surveys\n- Document 3-5 concrete contributions with numbers (revenue impact, cost savings, projects shipped)\n- Know your target number — studies show asking for a specific figure outperforms ranges\n\nIn the meeting:\n- Schedule it separately, not during a performance review\n- Lead with your contributions, then present the market data as context\n- Frame it collaboratively: \"I want to stay long-term, and I think getting my comp to market rate makes that easier for both of us\"\n\nIf declined, negotiate a timeline with specific conditions, documented in writing.","model_id":"perplexity/llama-3.1-sonar-large-128k-online"}}'::jsonb, true, '2026-06-10'
